Use the diamonds dataset that comes with R

data(diamonds)
head(diamonds)

Count the number of rows by clarity

sum(!is.na(diamonds$clarity))
## [1] 53940

What are the unique values for cut?

distinct(diamonds, diamonds$cut)

Tabulate the frequency (no of diamonds) by cut

diamonds_by_cut <- summarise(group_by(diamonds,cut),diamondcount = n())
diamonds_by_cut

Find the mean carat size by color

carat_size_by_color<- diamonds %>% group_by(color) %>% summarise_at(vars(carat), funs(mean(., na.rm=TRUE)))
carat_size_by_color

Use a bar chart to find which cut has the most amount of diamonds

ggplot(data=diamonds_by_cut, aes(x=cut, y=diamondcount)) + geom_bar(stat= "identity", color="red", fill=rgb(0,1,1,0.7))

Check the distribution of the carat size. How can you describe the distribution?

ggplot(data=diamonds, aes(diamonds$carat, fill = diamonds$color)) + geom_histogram()+ ggtitle("Carat size distribution")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

As per above chart, diamonds count are inverse proportionately distributed with respective to carat size.

Is there a relationship between carat size and price? Check using a graph.

ggplot(data=diamonds, aes(diamonds$carat,diamonds$price,color=factor(color))) + geom_point() + geom_jitter()

ggplot(diamonds, aes(carat, price)) + geom_line(color="red")

ggplot(diamonds, aes(carat, price)) + geom_smooth(color="red")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

As per above charts, diamond price is directly proportionate with respective to carat size.

Which color has the maximum variability in the price? Use a graph to find out.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(color, price, color = factor(color))) + geom_boxplot() + geom_jitter()
